,Recommended,327390,13396501,"Posted: 15 December, 2014",all,Panick,"I played a ton of this game back when it first came out and it is one I fondly remember. It was a great game in it's day and is still well worth playing but it is a very simple game layered with a thin veneer of fake complexity. Tailing someone, tracking someone, doing wiretaps are all the long way round to get the info you want. The best and fastest way to get loads of info in this game is to break into a place and crack some safes and take some pictures. You'll walk out with loads of intel that would've taken you hours to get any of the other ways.It's a fun game for a few hours and worth it for the nostalgia but everyone out there who is saying it needs a remake is dead wrong. The elements of Covert Action have been done in dozens of other games in more modern implementations. Deus Ex: Human Revolution does a lot of this stuff very well. Then there are the Splinter Cell games, Alpha Protocol and the newer Fallouts that all share some elements with Covert Action but have done them in more modern ways. And I suspect that Sid Meier is aware of that since it's one of the few games he hasn't seen fit to revisit."
